The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Prominent value investor Rakesh Jhunjhunwala has picked up a 16 per cent stake in Tops Security. He has also been inducted into the board of the company. The company is targeting a turnover of Rs 250 crore this fiscal following a major expansion and consolidation drive it is carrying out at present.

 Satyam Computer Services has bagged a multi-million dollar contract from INVISTA, an international player in polymer and fibre business, to provide its application maintenance system operations for the latter?s five clusters across the globe for three years. 

 Sutherland Global Services has been selected by the JD Power Certified Technology Service amp; Support Standards Board for defining the criteria for best practices for the board?s new support programme. The programme recognises excellence in technology services.

 Ashok Leyland has received the BS7799 certification for its information security management systems and became the first auto manufacturer in India accorded with this certification. The company?s Data Centre at Ennore has secured this certification.

 Maks Biscuits has commenced production at its newly set up factory in Hooghly from last Sunday. The company will market 32 different biscuits under the brand name of Maks. 

 Birla Power Solutions has bagged a two-year contract from Unicef for supplying generators at its different centres in the country. The contract is worth Rs 10 crore.

 Whyte amp; Mackay has sold the final bottle of its limited-edition malt whisky, The Dalmore 62 Years Old single highland malt Scotch whisky, at a price of ?30,000, approximately Rs 21 lakh. 

 Raymond has said it will set up a 50:50 joint venture with Lanificio Fedora of Italy at a cost of Rs 40 crore. 

